	<div id="share">
		<ul><li><p id="print"><a href="javascript:window.print();">Print this Page</a></li></ul>
	
	</div>
	
	
	
	
		
			<p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><font size="3"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial">The University of Central Florida accepted a $2 million donation from </span><city /><place /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial">Orlando</span></place /></city /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"> philanthropists John and Carrie Morgridge today, April 1, launching an effort to raise more money for a new national reading center on campus.</span></font></p><p /><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"></span></p><p /><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><font size="3"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial">The </span><place /><placename /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial">Morgridge</span></placename /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"> </span><placename /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial">National</span></placename /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"> </span><placename /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial">Reading</span></placename /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"> </span><placetype /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial">Center</span></placetype /></place /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"> would help parents and teachers learn about the most successful approaches nationwide to helping children become better readers. </span><place /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial">Central Florida</span></place /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"> teachers and parents would be able to visit the center online or in person to access top-notch reading strategies for children of all ages.</span></font></p><p /><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"></span></p><p /><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><font size="3"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial">UCF President John Hitt and </span><place /><placetype /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial">College</span></placetype /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"> of </span><placename /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial">Education Dean Sandra Robinson</span></placename /></place /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"> honored the Morgridges and discussed the proposed center at a ceremony Friday, April 1, at the </span><place /><placename /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial">UCF</span></placename /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"> </span><placename /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial">Teaching</span></placename /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"> </span><placetype /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial">Academy</span></placetype /></place /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial">. The UCF Board of Trustees on Thursday approved the centers name, and state legislators also must approve the name.</span></font></p><p /><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"></span></p><p /><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"><font size="3">Across the nation, there are so many effective strategies for helping children to learn to read, but we need better ways to communicate those ideas, Robinson said. We want to help stakeholders from throughout the nation find and share the most successful strategies to teach reading to children, and we want to give teachers more professional development opportunities so they can become better reading teachers.</font></span></p><p /><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"></span></p><p /><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><font size="3"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial">John and Carrie Morgridges $2 million donation, which will be matched with $1.75 million in state funds, is the largest ever pledged to the UCF College of Education. The gift is also one of the largest ever pledged to a college of education at a public university in </span><state /><place /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial">Florida.</span></font></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><font size="3"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"> </span></font></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><font size="3"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"></span></font><font size="3"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial">Half of the Morgridges donation will help to pay for a new building that likely would be next to the </span><place /><placetype /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial">College</span></placetype /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"> of </span><placename /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial">Education</span></placename /></place /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial">. The other half of the donation will be placed in an endowment to fund programming and operating costs after the center opens.</span></font></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><font size="3"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"> </span></font></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><font size="3"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"></span></font><font size="3"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial">&quot;This will truly be a transformational gift for our university,&quot; Hitt said during the ceremony Friday. &quot;John and Carrie, thank you for caring about our nation's literacy and thank you for your faith in UCF.&quot;</span></span></font></p><p /><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"><font size="3"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"></span></font></span></p><p /><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"><font size="3"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"></span></font></span></p><p /><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"><font size="3"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"></span></font></span></p><p /><p /><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"></span></p><p><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"><font size="3"></font></span></p><p /><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><font size="3"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial">UCF plans to raise a total of $11.2 million for construction and the centers endowment. The design and construction phases are expected to take about two years, and their timing will depend on the success of fund-raising efforts.</span></font></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><font size="3"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"> </span></font></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><font size="3"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"></span></font><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"><font size="3">John and Carrie Morgridge became interested in early childhood literacy when their two children -- John, an eighth-grader, and Michelle, a sixth-grader -- were young. The couples passion for reading seemed natural, especially because John Morgridges mother and grandmother were teachers.</font></span></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"> </span></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"></span><font size="3"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial">In 2002, the Morgridges moved to </span><place /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial">Central Florida</span></place /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"> from </span><state /><place /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial">Colorado</span></place /></state /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial">. Since then, the Morgridges have contributed more than $5 million to expand the Reading Recovery program to </span><state /><place /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial">Colorado</span></place /></state /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"> first-graders who are at the bottom 10 percent of their class.</span></font></p><p /><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"></span></p><p /><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"><font size="3">The Morgridges donated $100,000 last year to UCFs Florida Literacy and Reading Excellence program. Known as FLaRE, the program distributes information about literacy instruction and assessments statewide.</font></span></p><p /><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"></span></p><p /><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><font size="3"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial">The </span><place /><placename /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial">Morgridge</span></placename /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"> </span><placename /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial">National</span></placename /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"> </span><placename /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial">Reading</span></placename /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"> </span><placetype /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial">Center</span></placetype /></place /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"> would build on the reading resources UCF already provides through FLaRE and Reading First, a professional development program for kindergarten through third-grade teachers. Reading First focuses on the most important components of reading, including phonics, vocabulary and comprehension, and the best ways to assess how well students can read.</span></font></p><p /><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"></span></p><p /><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"><font size="3">The new center would expand those pursuits to a national level and would be dedicated to ensuring that educators, policy makers, nonprofit groups and families have access to the best research available on improving childrens reading skills. </font></span></p><p /><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"></span></p><p /><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"><font size="3"><span></span>(Dean Sandra) Robinson has phenomenal vision, Carrie Morgridge said. The best practices at UCF get me excited about teaching and education because they understand the whole child and the whole process. It isnt just one program for one child; its many things together.</font></span></p><p /><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"></span></p><p /><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0in 0in 0pt"><font size="3"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial">The reading center would collect information about the most successful reading initiatives in all 50 states, </span><country-region /><place /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial">U.S.</span></place /></country-region /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial"> commonwealths and territories and schools on military bases, and it would showcase childrens books by top authors. The showcase, and possibly some other programs, could be established in temporary locations before the new building opens.</span></font></p>
		
	
		
			<br />
		
	
